s venerated as those of the Apostle but was created only in 251 by Pope Cornelius. Drawing on the most up-to-date archaeological evidence, he describes a cityscape that was at once Christian and pagan, mirroring the personality of its ruler.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aArchitecture paléochrétiennexItaliexRome. 0aArchitecturexItaliexRome. 0aArchitecturexItalyxRome. 0aArchitecturezItalyzRome. 0aArchitecture, Early ChristianxItalyxRome. 0aArchitecture, Early ChristianzItalyzRome. 0aChristianisme et artxItaliexRome. 0aChristianity and artxItalyxRome. 0aChristianity and artzItalyzRome. 7aARCHITECTURE / History / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300129717423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300129717.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles